      <hedline>
        <hl1>Bush and Gore, on the Battleground of Ideas</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Arnold L Cabasso letter on Richard A Epstein's Sept 7 article opposes proposals by George W Bush and Al Gore to subsidize drug costs for elderly under Medicare</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Competing to Make Things Worse,'' by Richard A. Epstein (Op-Ed, Sept. 7):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Competing to Make Things Worse,'' by Richard A. Epstein (Op-Ed, Sept. 7):</p>
        <p>It's about time that there was some criticism of both major candidates as they fall over each other to give a new entitlement to the wealthiest segment of the population. Yes, it's true that medications are expensive, but it is also true that the over-65 cohort can best afford them.</p>
        <p>Having Medicare pay for prescription drugs will eliminate the possibility of paying down the deficit or force the other, less well-off age groups to subsidize the elderly, who for the most part can afford them. Having a less ambitious plan to help those of any age with catastrophic medication costs would be more fair and less expensive.</p>
        <p>ARNOLD L. CABASSO  Fair Lawn, N.J., Sept. 7, 2000</p>
      </block>
